## The Modified Brilliant Split

The Modified Brilliant Split is the most consequential decision in the 1ct cushion cut market — and the decision that most buyers do not know they are making when they begin searching for a cushion cut diamond ring.

[![Cushion cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold solitaire on white background](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/505021/505021_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box3_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**What the split is.** Every cushion cut diamond falls into one of two sub-types: the cushion modified brilliant (GIA certificate reads "Cushion Modified Brilliant") or the cushion brilliant (GIA certificate reads "Cushion Brilliant"). The cushion modified brilliant has additional pavilion facets that break the stone's light return into many small, uniform reflections — the "crushed ice" pattern. The cushion brilliant has fewer, larger pavilion facets that create distinct, directional flash patterns — often called "chunky" facets or "pillow" facets.

**What the split looks like at 1ct.** At 6.5mm face-up, the two sub-types are clearly visually distinct under normal viewing conditions. The modified brilliant at 1ct produces a dense, sparkling, uniformly bright appearance — high in photographic appeal, performs strongly under direct light. The cushion brilliant at 1ct produces a smaller number of distinct, visible flashes — larger individual light returns, more visible fire (rainbow dispersion), more three-dimensional character under varied lighting. Side by side in a jeweller's case, most buyers immediately prefer one or the other: the modified brilliant reads as brighter and more uniformly brilliant; the cushion brilliant reads as more characterful and more visually interesting under candlelight or restaurant lighting.

**Why most buyers end up with a modified brilliant without choosing it.** Blue Nile's default cushion filter returns cushion modified brilliants in the majority. The GIA grading report description "Cushion Modified Brilliant" is not prominent on most retailers' listing pages — it appears in the full report but not always in the thumbnail or listing. Many buyers purchase a cushion cut expecting the chunky, fire-rich performance of the cushion brilliant and receive the uniform brightness of the modified brilliant. This is The Modified Brilliant Split: the moment of discovering that "cushion cut" contains two meaningfully different stones, and that you chose one without knowing there was a choice.

**How to navigate The Modified Brilliant Split at 1ct.** Watch the HD 360° video at Blue Nile before purchasing. A modified brilliant at 1ct will show continuous, uniform glitter across the face-up surface with no distinct flash zones. A cushion brilliant will show distinct, larger flashes with clear fire zones — patches of colour and directional white light. If the video shows pure, uniform sparkle throughout: modified brilliant. If the video shows distinct larger flashes or clearly visible fire: cushion brilliant. Choose based on which performance matches your intended use and aesthetic preference, not based on which stone appears first in the filter results.

