diamond-details/22397388?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">1.00ct Cushion Modified</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>D / VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong>$5,611</strong></td><td>6 reviews</td></tr></tbody></table>

**Reading the 1ct natural table.** The value-maximum choice is the [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Ideal at $1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). G colour at 1ct in yellow or rose gold is visually colourless — the 6.5mm face-up size does not make G body warmth visible under normal conditions in warm metal. VS1 at 1ct is reliably eye-clean across all cushion sub-types without video verification. The $173 step from G-VS1 to G-VVS2 ($2,022) trades clarity for clarity — a sideways step with no visible benefit at 1ct.

**The G-to-F colour decision at 1ct.** The [GIA 1ct F-VS1 at $2,064](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25944037?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs $173 more than the G-VS1. In white gold or platinum, F colour at 1ct is the minimum that ensures no visible body warmth — G may show slight warmth in platinum at 6.5mm face-up to a trained eye in direct comparison. In yellow or rose gold, the F vs G distinction is invisible. Choose F for white metal settings; save $173 with G in warm metal settings.

**The D colour premium at 1ct.** The step from F-VS1 ($2,064) to D-VS1 ($4,410) is $2,346 — more than doubling the stone price for two colour grades that are not visible to the naked eye in any setting. D colour at 1ct in a cushion modified brilliant is a certificate purchase, not a visual quality purchase. For buyers who specifically want D on the grading report — for sentimental, gifting, or documentation reasons — the [GIA 1ct D-VVS1 at $4,873](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29255833?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the strongest value in the D tier. For buyers who want the best visible quality at 1ct: stay at G-VS1 or F-VS1.

> "At 1ct, the colour-clarity-price relationship is the most transparent in the cushion market. The entire quality range from G-VS1 ($1,891) to D-VVS1 ($4,873) is laid out clearly, the differences are visible in the data if not always in the stone, and the buyer has genuine choice between multiple options at every tier.
>
> My consistent advice at 1ct: G-VS1 or F-VS1 in your chosen metal, whichever sub-type you chose after watching the video, in the setting that best serves your intended look. The total ring cost for a GIA G-VS1 cushion modified brilliant in a rose gold pavé solitaire is approximately $2,600–$3,000 from Blue Nile — a complete, beautiful, GIA-certified cushion engagement ring for under $3,000. That is the 1ct cushion market working as it should." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

